===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|spete}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|spittan}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} (compare Danish {{m|da|spytte}}, Swedish {{m|sv|spotta}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*sp(y)ēw}}, {{m|ine-pro|*spyū}} <ref>Ayto, John, ''Dictionary of Word Origins'', Arcade Publishing, New York, 1990</ref>, of imitiative origin (see [[spew]])<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=spit spew], [[w:Online Etymology Dictionary|Online Etymology Dictionary]], Douglas Harper</ref>

In the Wycliffe Bible (Middle English), one finds ''spete'' (infinitive), ''spetyng'' (gerund), ''spetide'' (past), and ''spete'' (past participle).
====Verb====
{{en-verb|spits|spitting|spat|past2=spit}} The past tense and past participle ''spit'' are the more common forms used by speakers in America, but they are also used often enough by speakers of British and Commonwealth English to be listed as alternative forms by Collins and the Oxford Online Dictionaries. It is an older form. A non-standard past participle form is [[spitten]].

# {{label|en|intransitive|transitive}} To [[evacuate]] ([[saliva]] or another substance) from the [[mouth]].
#:{{RQ:Authorized Version|Mark|8|23}}
#::And he took the blind man by the hand, and led him out of the town; and when he had '''spit''' on his eyes, and put his hands upon him, he asked him if he saw ought. And he looked up, and said, I see men as trees, walking.
#: ''The teacher told her to '''spit''' out her bubble gum.''
#* '''1994''', {{w|Stephen Fry}}, ''{{w|The Hippopotamus}}'' Chapter 2
#*: At the very moment he cried out, David realised that what he had run into was only the Christmas tree. Disgusted with himself at such cowardice, he '''spat''' a needle from his mouth, stepped back from the tree and listened. There were no sounds of any movement upstairs: no shouts, no sleepy grumbles, only a gentle tinkle from the decorations as the tree had recovered from the collision.
# To rain or snow slightly, or with sprinkles.
#* Charles Dickens
#*: It had been '''spitting''' with rain.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[utter]] [[violently]].
#* '''1915''', [[w:Amélie Rives Troubetzkoy|Amélie Rives (Princess Troubetzkoy)]], ''Shadows of Flames'', page 240&nbsp;[http://books.google.com/books?id=-9AcAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA240&dq=spat]:
#*: "Why, you little emasculated Don Juan— You—" he '''spat''' an unmentionable name— "d'you think I'd fight one of your tin-soldier farces with you? Clear out!"
#* '''2004''', [[w:Mark Gatiss|Mark Gatiss]], [[w:The Vesuvius Club|''The Vesuvius Club'']], 2005 [[w:Pocket Books|Pocket Books]] edition, ISBN 0743483790, chapter 3, page 23&nbsp;[http://books.google.com/books?id=d9F9MUiOQD4C&pg=PA23&dq=spat]:
#*: "''Gentleman?'' You?" he '''spat'''.
# {{label|en|transitive|slang|hip-hop}} To [[utter]].
#* '''2005''', Giselle Zado Wasfie, ''So Fly''
#*: A group of black guys were '''spitting''' rhymes in the corner, slapping hands and egging one another on.

